  "summary": "# Weekly Market Briefing \u2014 Week Ending April 12, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 1. Market Overview\n\nBroad indices posted a strong rally this week. **SPY gained +3.12%** to $679.46 and **QQQ surged +3.84%**, reflecting outsized strength in large-cap tech. Small caps participated meaningfully, with **IWM up +3.54%**, suggesting broad-based risk appetite rather than a narrow mega-cap rally. DIA lagged slightly at +2.67%, indicating the Dow's value-heavy composition was a modest headwind. Volume across SPY (60.3M) and QQQ (44.0M) was robust, lending credibility to the move.\n\n## 2. Sector Performance\n\n**Outperformers:** Technology (**XLK +4.27%**) led all sectors, followed closely by Industrials (**XLI +4.20%**), Consumer Discretionary (**XLY +3.53%**), and Materials (**XLB +3.46%**). This is a classic pro-growth, risk-on rotation.\n\n**Underperformers:** Energy (**XLE -4.59%**) was the clear laggard, likely reflecting declining oil prices or demand concerns. Consumer Staples (**XLP -0.35%**) and Healthcare (**XLV +0.70%**) also trailed, consistent with money rotating out of defensive positions. Telecom-heavy dividend names VZ (-4.92%) and T (-5.59%) reinforced the defensive weakness.\n\nThe divergence between XLK and XLE \u2014 nearly a **9-point spread** \u2014 is among the widest weekly sector gaps we've seen recently.\n\n## 3. Notable Movers\n\n- **AVGO +18.17%** \u2014 The week's standout performer. Volume of 25.5M signals institutional conviction, though the P/E of 72.4 warrants attention.\n- **AMZN +12.03%** \u2014 Heavy volume (45.5M) accompanied the move. Possible catalyst from earnings expectations or business segment news.\n- **AMD +11.29%** \u2014 Semiconductor momentum continues; P/E at 93.5 reflects significant growth priced in.\n- **META +9.92%** \u2014 Strong move on moderate volume. P/E of 26.8 remains relatively reasonable among mega-caps.\n- **SNOW -18.92%** \u2014 The week's biggest decliner. A move of this magnitude on 11M volume likely reflects an earnings miss or guidance cut.\n- **PLTR -13.43%** \u2014 Sharp selloff on very high volume (65.5M). At a P/E of 203.3, the stock remains vulnerable to sentiment shifts.\n- **CRM -10.62%** \u2014 Notable given its more reasonable P/E of 21.1; worth investigating the catalyst.\n- **XOM -6.65% / CVX -5.18%** \u2014 Energy majors tracked the broader sector decline.\n\n## 4. Key Metrics\n\nValuation dispersion remains extreme. **TSLA (323.1x)** and **PLTR (203.3x)** carry speculative-grade multiples, while **T (8.7x)** and **VZ (11.3x)** trade at deep-value levels. The broad market P/E on SPY (~27x) sits above historical averages.\n\n**Crypto was flat to slightly negative** across the board (BTC -0.49%, ADA -4.79%), diverging from the equity risk-on tone \u2014 a notable decorrelation.\n\n**Gold (GLD +2.22%) and silver (SLV +4.52%)** rallied alongside equities, suggesting persistent inflation hedging or geopolitical demand even amid risk appetite.\n\n## 5. Themes to Watch\n\n- **Tech earnings season** likely approaching \u2014 the AVGO/AMD/SNOW divergence suggests the market will reward execution and punish misses aggressively.\n- **Energy weakness** \u2014 monitor whether this reflects commodity fundamentals or broader macro signals.\n- **Gold rallying with equities** is unusual; watch for signals on inflation expectations or central bank policy.\n- **Bond markets were flat** (BND +0.23%, TLT -0.18%), implying the equity rally isn't being driven by rate-cut optimism. Worth monitoring.\n\n---\n\n*Prepared for internal distribution. Not investment advice.*",
